<DOCNO>FT924-1112</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLTALADIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921219
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 92 / The Lex Column: Asda Group
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Archie Norman must be something of a local hero in Asda's home town of
Leeds. In little more than a year he has turned round a grocery chain that
was heading for severe financial trouble. As yesterday's interim figures
revealed, Asda's trading decline has been halted, its debt mountain reduced,
and its profitability restored. Shareholders who backed Asda's emergency
rights issue at 35p must be feeling smug: the shares closed yesterday at
61p.
Sceptics will mutter that it is all too good to last. And they may well be
right. Although Mr Norman has undoubtedly made an impressive start, he has
yet to show a strategy for reviving long-term growth. It will be hard to pay
down borrowings of Pounds 472m from normal trading activities. A capital
expenditure budget of Pounds 130m looks inadequate to launch a discount
chain such as Dales. A further Pounds 200m of sales will be lost to
competitor openings this year.
The company's management may seek to exploit its shining reputation by
staging a second rights issue. The City may be inclined to back it. But
Asda's long-term survival is still not secure. That overhanging doubt may
takethe wind out of the share price's recent rise.
</TEXT>
