<HEADLINE>
FT  19 DEC 92 / International Company News: BA warning over US jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Airways yesterday accused Washington of putting nearly 100,000 US
jobs at risk by linking its Dollars 750m offer for 44 per cent of USAir to
liberalisation of the UK-US aviation market.
The warning coincided with a last minute effort by Mr John Major, the prime
minister, to win Washington's approval for the deal during weekend talks
with President George Bush.
Sir Colin Marshall, BA's chief executive, claimed the US government's
apparent determination to make approval of the bid conditional on UK
liberalisation was 'entirely to the benefit of the three major US airlines'.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Delta Air Lines have led the campaign
to block the BA-USAir deal unless the US government can secure greater
access for US carriers into the London market.
Sir Colin said BA hoped the bid would be approved. But BA was disappointed
it appeared to hinge on bilateral issues which had no connection with the
commercial deal between the two airlines. 'For the US government, the
upholders of belief in freedom of capital and freedom of movement, to be
rejecting this deal, which clearly puts at risk the future of USAir, its
47,000 employees, and a similar number who are providers of services and
products, boggles the mind.'
</TEXT>
