<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / International Company News: Navistar in tentative deal with
union over health care
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NAVISTAR International, the Chicago-based truck and engine manufacturer,
last night Wednesday announced it had reached a tentative agreement with the
UAW, the auto workers' union, to trim retiree healthcare costs. The
agreement is expected to reduce Navistar's liability for retiree health care
and insurance benefits to Dollars 1bn from Dollars 2.6bn.
The company said it would resume negotiating a collective bargaining
agreement with its unions on January 8 which was aimed at changing
post-retirement healthcare benefits for active employees.
The UAW has been leading negotiations with Navistar since mid-October, when
the union and the company agreed to set aside an Ohio lawsuit. The company
had contended that its retiree benefits put it at a Dollars 200m annual cost
disadvantage to its competitors, and that it would enter bankruptcy if the
cost burden were not reduced. A 1985 restructuring left the company with
three retirees for each active employee.
The deal with the union requires Navistar to issue 255m new shares of common
stock to a trust fund for current and future retirees. A new profit-sharing
programme will make payments into the same fund. The company has 251m shares
outstanding, and last quarter its sales translated into little more than 3.5
cents per share.
In turn, retirees will be required to share in the costs of their medical
benefits by paying premiums and deductibles.
Navistar said it was suspending the quarterly dividend on its series G
preferred stock until the legal process involving the benefits restructuring
was complete, and the new healthcare programme was implemented.
</TEXT>
