<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / International Company News: Delta cuts its dividend to 5
cents a share
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DELTA Air Lines, one of the three largest US carriers, is cutting its
quarterly dividend from 30 cents a share to just 5 cents, in an attempt to
ride out difficult conditions in the industry and the problematic
integration of transatlantic assets it acquired from the now-defunct Pan Am.
Delta also announced another big cost-cutting package, involving a Dollars
600m reduction in spending on facilities and ground equipment over the next
three years, deferrals of another Dollars 400m of aircraft orders over the
same period, and salary reductions aimed at saving around Dollars 180m a
year.
Earlier this year, Delta announced that it was slashing about Dollars 5bn
from its capital spending up until 2001, and implementing a 'profit
improvement plan' designed to prune Dollars 375m from operating costs in the
current financial year. The airline has shed around 5,000 jobs over the past
12 months.
The company, which has virtually doubled in size during the past five years
and has become a significant international airline via the Pan Am deal in
late-1991, said it was trying to avoid lay-offs among permanent employees.
Atlanta-based Delta has long been famed for its paternalistic approach to
employee relations. The carrier has talked enthusiastically about the 'Delta
family' and prided itself on a no-redundancy policy.
Mr Ron Allen, chairman, acknowledged that the salary reductions, which
involve a 5 per cent pay cut for all non-contract staff, was the first
company-wide pay reduction in the airline's history.
Delta gave no details of the aircraft order deferrals, but it has 162
aircraft on firm order and 259 on option.
Most of these are Boeing and McDonnell Douglas aircraft, and a spokesman
said that orders for nine Airbus Industrie A-310 aircraft, due in 1993, were
expected to go ahead.
</TEXT>
