<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / Money Markets: French cash rates rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of France decided not to raise official interest rates at its
Thursday repurchase operation in spite of continuing pressure on the French
franc on the foreign exchanges, writes James Blitz.
There had been much expectation in recent days that France would increase
the rates at which it offers cash to banks through the five to 10-day
lending window, in order to reverse the currency's fall to within a centime
of its ERM floor against the D-Mark.
The authorities yesterday left the intervention rate unchanged at 9.10 per
cent, while the five to 10-day repurchase rate stayed at 10 per cent. The
franc briefly fell below the FFr3.42 level against the D-Mark in the wake of
the move, but there were no signs of significantly greater pressure on the
French currency.
One London-based dealer suggested that the French decision was, tactically,
the right move. He said that a rise in rates would have created a new
atmosphere of crisis over the franc. The French authorities have realised
that the market is now putting a new premium on growth, and actually fears
that rate increases are fundamentally bad for the economy, he added.
Cash rates in the French franc market again firmed yesterday, with
three-month money rising as high as 12 per cent. In the franc futures
market, there was erratic trading in the March contract, which opened at
around 90.40 and fell back to 90.25 on fears of the rate rise. The
authorities' decision pushed the contract up again, to close a net 3 basis
points higher at 90.43.
Short-dated Euromark futures rose sharply yesterday in spite of what was
considered a hawkish monthly report from the Bundesbank. The March contract
rose 12 basis points to close at 92.05, a level which assumes that
three-month money in late spring will be at 7.95 per cent.
Rates in the German cash market softened a little yesterday, but remained on
the comparatively high side because of end-of-year pressures. Three-month
money averaged about 9.07 per cent yeasterday, having been at around 8.90
per cent last week.
In the sterling market, three-month money was unchanged at 7 1/4 per cent.
The Bank of England forecast a shortage of Pounds 400m, which was fully
removed.
</TEXT>
