<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / German takeover rules criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE chief of Germany's leading fund management company yesterday called for
an overhaul of his country's corporate takeover rules.
Mr Christian Strenger, chief executive of DWS, the Deutsche Bank fund
management arm which has DM58bn (Pounds 23bn) under management, said that
shareholders in German companies were disadvantaged because of the lack of a
takeover code.
He said German banks and companies should devise a code of practice on such
issues as disclosure and the treatment of minority shareholders in
takeovers. The call comes a week after Calpers, the big US pension fund,
condemned voting rights restrictions at many large German companies,
including Deutsche Bank, DWS's parent company. Companies said they needed
these rules in the absence of formal takeover regulations.
Mr Strenger said that once his proposals were adopted, it would be possible
for companies to abandon their voting restrictions, which would be welcomed
by domestic and foreign shareholders as a way of enhancing share prices.
There are very limited rules for takeovers in Germany. Shareholdings need
only be disclosed when they reach 25 per cent - in contrast to 3 per cent in
the UK - nor is there is a requirement to treat all shareholders equally.
This means that it is standard practice for companies to seek effective
control of another company by acquiring a simple majority of shares or a
blocking minority. There is no requirement for companies to pay a premium
for corporate control, which Mr Strenger believes is to the detriment of
shareholders.
'It would cost very little for companies to comply with such proposals, in
relation to the damage that is done to the equity market as a result of the
current state of affairs,' he said.
Mr Strenger's remarks reflect his concern, as head of Germany's leading
provider of investment funds to private individuals, that Germans are averse
to investing in equities. Germans prefer buying bonds and only 10 per cent
of DWS's DM58bn is invested in equities.
Approximately half the shares in all Germany's quoted companies are owned by
banks, insurance companies, families and other long-term shareholders.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15
</PAGE>
