<PROFILE>_AN-CLRBYADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921218
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / The Lex Column: Bad checks at Barclays
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It almost beggars belief that a once great bank like Barclays could have run
up an exposure of Pounds 440m to a single customer on the basis of little
more than an expectation of indefinitely rising property values. Had its
loans to Imry been syndicated, the bank would not be in the embarrassing
position of making a Pounds 240m provision - enormous by any banking
standard, except perhaps on sovereign debt.
If the recriminations are likely to reverberate, the bank has at least found
an orderly way of sorting out the mess. Having written off the money it lent
to Marketchief to buy Imry in 1989, it is left with an exposure of Pounds
176m to a property company with sound management, net assets of Pounds 70m
and a portfolio worth about Pounds 300m which is pretty well fully let.
Since Barclays is now the beneficial owner of Imry, it stands to benefit
from any property market recovery.
Liquidation would have been a more likely result had Imry borrowed from a
syndicate. Cynics would say Barclays, too, could have chosen this route but
it would then have had to make an even larger provision. It may look silly
yet again if the property market continues to fall, though the existing
provision covers a quarter of its remaining exposure.
Besides, there are some more immediate consequences. To restore confidence
in its management, Barclays must find a banker of stature to work alongside
Mr Andrew Buxton. Its 1992 dividend decision has also become even more
agonising. The Pounds 165m provision to be charged in the current half is
larger than the market had generally expected. Since there has been no
discernible improvement in the lending climate since Black Wednesday,
provisions may tip the bank into pre-tax loss for 1992 instead of allowing a
small profit. That would make a maintained payout harder to justify.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
