FT  18 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tonight brings the last episodes in three dramas. In ITV's studiously odd
Gone To Seed the villainous Wesley (Peter Cook) thinks that the triplets'
garden centre is finally within his grasp (8.00). In Framed, the saga of a
super grass, Detective McKinnes (Timothy West) tries to tempt his squealer
into making a break for the spondulicks (9.00 ITV). In Son Of The Morning
Star (9.30 BBC1) General Custer fights Little Bighorn again, with Rosanna
Arquette looking decorative as his wife. ITV offers more human interest
journalism with hints of the 'Crimewatch' formula. Missing (10.40 some ITV
regions) aims to find missing people, and in addition to appeals for
information there is a record of a police sweep for young runaways in
London. A good deal of pretentious nonsense has been written about Triumph
Of The Will (12.05 BBC2), Leni Riefenstahl's notorious film about the 1934
Nazi party congress in Nuremburg. Whatever Riefenstahl herself may have
said, it obviously is propaganda, and very polished propaganda. Most of the
techniques were not new, but they were used more cleverly here than ever
before (12.05 BBC2).
