<DOCNO>FT924-1391</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLRBYACCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921218
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Lottery bill does not allay fears
of voluntary sector leaders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE bill has not allayed the fears of voluntary sector leaders that the
lottery will damage charities' fund-raising activities, Alan Pike writes.
Ms Judy Weleminsky, director of the National Council for Voluntary
Organisations, said the lottery was an ambitious and bold scheme, but a
number of safeguards for the voluntary sector must be addressed by MPs.
Charity managers have two related concerns. One is that the lottery will
reduce their income, particularly from sources like street collections and
small charity lotteries. The other is that national lottery proceeds will
not compensate for such a loss because charities will be only one of several
causes to benefit.
Some charity managers believe the voluntary sector's income will be reduced
unless 50 per cent of distributed lottery proceeds go to charities.
Mr Frank Flannery, managing director of UK Charity Lotteries - a
charity-owned organisation that runs lottery games - said provisions in the
bill to increase prizes in charity lotteries were a 'totally inadequate
safeguard.'
There was a grave danger that Pounds 260m currently raised by charity
lotteries would be completely wiped out by the national lottery.
The Institute of Charity Fundraising Managers said the voluntary sector
would be able to support the Bill only if the government provided
compensation for the potential downturn in charities' income.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
