<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Quotes of the year
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
'There is no point in going back to 1987 and 1988. The question is who's
going to get the economy moving, and anyone who thinks its the Labour party
must be stark staring bonkers'
Norman Lamont 1 April
'I am humble enough to recognise that I have made mistakes but politically
astute enough to know that I have forgotten what they are'
Michael Heseltine 3 April
'People in a democracy respect a leader who will say: 'I have not been right
all the way down the line; I have no monopoly of wisdom''
Neil Kinnock 3 April
'I am consulting with colleagues to inform them of the action I propose to
take in the wake of the election defeat. I will make a full statement on
Monday'
Neil Kinnock 9 April
'I got more egg on my face during the election than anyone - except for the
pollsters'
John Major 9 April
'The ERM is not an optional extra, an add-on to be jettisoned at the first
hint of trouble. It is and will remain at the very centre of our
macro-economic strategy.'
Norman Lamont 10 July
'Today has been an extremely difficult and turbulent day . . The government
has concluded that Britain's best interests are served by suspending our
membership of the exchange rate mechanism'
Norman Lamont 16 September
'The question is whether it is the prime minister or tabloid editors who
determine who should serve in the British cabinet'
David Mellor 24 September
'Last week the chancellor didn't just stop supporting the pound. He stopped
supporting the prime minister, leaving him floating downwards - to find his
own level'
Gordon Brown 28 September
'The opt-out prime minister leading a do-nothing government off the European
stage . . We were promised a new statesman, and what have we got instead?
The spectator'
John Smith 29 September
'Allowing the pound to float is not the outcome I sought, but nor is it the
sort of catastrophe that some have tried to suggest'
Norman Lamont 8 October
'I told you so'
Sir Alan Walters 8 October
'These decisions have been taken only after the most careful consideration.
They are painful, but essential to secure the industry's future and cannot
be postponed'
Michael Heseltine on the pit closure plan 13 October
'The consultation period will be aimed at considering all views without
restriction . . It will be a genuine review'
Michael Heseltine 21 October
'Progress has been made. It is not enough. It has taken six months, but six
months in the history of Ireland is but an evening gone'
Sir Patrick Mayhew announcing collapse of Ulster talks 11 November
'I was in Brussels with M Delors, negotiating our contribution to the
European Community, and to have to leave that meeting to telephone my
private office to answer questions about whether I had bought a bottle of
wine in Paddington, and the price of that wine, was the height of absurdity'
Norman Lamont 4 December
'The summit that put the (European) Community back together'
John Major on Edinburgh 13 December
</TEXT>
