<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Sitting suspended as Scots protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A DOZEN fiery Scottish Labour backbenchers disrupted the Commons yesterday
by defying Miss Betty Boothroyd, the speaker, and forcing her to suspend the
sitting for just under three hours.
In vain attempts to secure a government statement on proposals to confer
trust status on more Scottish hospitals, they capped two rounds of bogus
points of order by staging a disorderly demonstration.
Led by Mr Ernie Ross, MP for Dundee West, and Mr George Galloway, MP for
Glasgow Hillhead, the small group of protesters, mostly from the Scotland
United faction, stood in the centre of the Chamber in front of the mace,
symbol of the Crown's authority.
Mr Michael Morris, the deputy speaker, ordered an initial five-minute
suspension when his appeals for seasonal goodwill as MPs prepared to
disperse for the three-week Christmas recess were ignored.
When the sitting resumed Miss Boothroyd took the chairbut her attempts to
persuade the protesters to comply with the rules of the House were no more
successful than those made by Mr Morris.
In ordering the more prolonged suspension Miss Boothroyd made clear her
determination to ensure that nothing interfered with the final item on the
agenda - her announcement of the measures given royal assent by the Queen.
When the House reassembled at three o'clock Miss Boothroyd announced that
three measures - the Consolidated Fund (Number 3) Act, the Sea Fish
(Conservation) Act, and the Civil Service (Management Functions) Act - had
received royal assent.
She immediately adjourned the House and the deputy serjeant-at-arms removed
the mace before protesters could take any further action.
</TEXT>
