<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / South-east jobless rate above 10%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE than one in 10 of the workforce in the south-east of England was
unemployed in November, highlighting the destructive force of the recession
in Britain's most important economic region.
The Department of Employment reported yesterday that the number of
unemployment benefit claimants in the south-east increased by 17,700 to a
seasonally adjusted 916,800 last month, taking the region's jobless rate to
a record high of 10.1 per cent from 9.9 per cent in October.
The south-east's unemployment rate in November was nearly three times the
3.6 per cent for the region in early 1990.
In Greater London alone, unemployment rose to 11.3 per cent in November from
11.2 per cent in October, making the capital the third worst region for
unemployment in the UK after Northern Ireland and the north.
November's 41,100 jump to 2.9m in UK seasonally adjusted unemployment was
the 31st consecutive monthly rise in the claimant count since the spring of
1990, bringing unemployment to its highest level since April 1987. Since
early 1990 - when unemployment bottomed out - registered unemployment in the
UK has risen by more than 1.31m, lifting the national unemployment rate to
10.3 per cent last month.
Total unadjusted unemployment was 10.1 per cent or 2,864,069 in November, up
49,657 on October's level.
Yesterday's jobless figures gave only a partial picture of the shakeout in
the labour market since the start of the recession. Employment department
figures showed that the UK workforce in employment fell to 24.95m in the
third quarter of this year, nearly 2m down from its 26.92m peak in the
second quarter of 1990.
According to the department's labour force survey, also published yesterday,
the percentage of the UK population over 16 that is economically active fell
to 63.1 per cent in the summer from 64.3 per cent in the spring of 1990.
The latest statistics suggest the labour market shakeout will continue for
some time. The November jump in unemployment was higher than the 35,000
increase generally expected in the City and above the latest six and
three-month averages of 32,200 and 32,600 respectively.
The 399,000 fall in the UK workforce in the third quarter was the highest on
record. The inflow of claimants at job centres has also been running at a
higher monthly rate in the second half of this year than in the first half.
The stock of unfilled vacancies at Jobcentres rose 2,600 to a
seasonally-adjusted 100,800 last month, but there were about 20,000 fewer
vacancies than in the first quarter of the year.
The latest UK figures show a big difference in unemployment rates between
males - where seasonally adjusted unemployment set a post-second-world-war
high of 13.8 per cent in November - and females, where the UK unemployment
rate was 5.6 per cent.
A notable feature of the year to October was the steep 241,000 drop in
manufacturing employment. The latest figures also show that 233,000 service
industry jobs were lost in the third quarter alone.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
