<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / Councils to defy 1.5% pay ceiling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO Conservative-controlled councils that have opted out of national pay
agreements are to breach the government's 1.5 per cent pay ceiling for
public-sector workers.
South Oxfordshire District Council is likely to pay an extra 3.6 per cent
from April and Tandridge District Council in Surrey will increase pay by 4
per cent from January 1.
The councils are likely to apply the 1.5 per cent increase in 1994.
Both said they agreed on the deals just before last month's Autumn
Statement, which signalled the pay curb.
Most other councils that have opted out of national pay negotiations over
the past few years do not intend to breach the government's ceiling for
public-sector workers.
Similar decisions are being made by other independent public-sector
employers, including National Health Service trusts that are able to
negotiate pay locally for new staff.
Local Government Chronicle estimates that nine out of 15 local authorities
with settlement dates between January and April do not intend to breach the
1.5 per cent limit.
The magazine reports in its latest issue that Surrey County Council will
join Kent and Buckinghamshire in opting for local pay bargaining.
White-collar workers and residential staff will, however, have the option of
staying in the national agreement.
Other local authorities - especially in the Home Counties where recruitment
difficulties are greatest - are considering whether to remain within the
system.
Conservative-controlled Kent County Council will stick to a 1.5 per cent pay
increase for its 14,000 staff. Buckinghamshire County Council is expected to
follow suit.
Mr John Redwood, the local government minister, has written to all the
opted-out councils 'seeking co-operation' at what he described as an
extremely difficult time.
Breakaway action by organisations such as councils and NHS trusts does not
normally indicate lower pay; most want more flexibility and the ability to
reward merit.
Few NHS trusts have broken away from rates nationally negotiated by the pay
review bodies, although they are free to do so for newly recruited staff.
</TEXT>
