<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / Frugal Christmas in store: Chris Tighe finds shoppers in
widely separated retail centres sharing the same worries about their festive
spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CAUTIOUS consumerism is the dominant theme of Christmas 1992 in two urban
retail centres 297 miles apart.
Croydon's Whitgift Centre and Newcastle upon Tyne's Eldon Square serve
communities with different historic roots, but they are united by the impact
of the recession and concern about Britain's economic outlook.
In both centres the signs are the same - shoppers are shunning credit cards,
are fearful of debt and are thinking hard about purchases. This is a
Christmas when 'Pounds 1 off' matters. Christmas shopping at both began a
week late. Extended evening openings and - at the Whitgift Centre - Sunday
trading have probably exacerbated the trend, giving shoppers more
last-minute buying time providing they have money to spend or the
inclination to go into debt.
After a difficult trading year and a slow start to Christmas, much hangs on
this crucial last week. 'We take 12 per cent of our annual turnover in the
last eight days,' says Croydon jeweller Mr Ray Lyons.
The Whitgift Centre is a 1.25m sq ft, partly covered complex with 126 shops
which opened in 1969 and is owned by Barclays de Zoete Wedd and the Whitgift
Foundation. Mr Rod Wood, the manager, forecasts that pre-Christmas takings
will be between 4 per cent and 7 per cent down on last year. 'Some shops are
up, but they're the few,' he says.
Eldon Square is a 1.5m sq ft covered complex with 160 shops that was
completed in stages from 1976 and is owned by property development group
Capital and Counties, Newcastle City Council and Shell Pension Trust. Mr
Gordon Allanson, the manager of Eldon Square, expects trade to be '1 per
cent to 2 per cent down on last year'.
Retailers' dizzy days of dramatic turnover growth based on high inflation
are over, he warns. 'We're going to have to get used to a different climate.
We must come to terms with being cost-conscious and not expecting big
year-on-year increases.' Realism has settled on shoppers as well. 'One could
boringly call it a practical Christmas,' says Mr Brian Forbes Turner,
chairman of the Eldon Square Merchants' Association and managing director of
the Bainbridge department store. 'People are looking at the sensible
purchases.'
A Croydon shopper says: 'Last year we bought my dad a silver-plated lighter
 -this year it'll be socks and boxer shorts.'
Children are the last to suffer - toys are classed as essentials and both
centres report strong sales in electronic items. The recession reached
Croydon before Newcastle. Eldon Square has only felt the full effects this
year with an unprecedented 10 receiverships. 'In terms of boom and recession
Newcastle tends to be 18 months to two years behind the south-east,' says Mr
Bill Black, Capital and Counties group manager.
Extensive office developments and prosperous housing areas gave Croydon
self-assurance in the 1980s, but now it is adjusting to harder times. Local
unemployment has touched 10 per cent this year and the borough's rate of
mortgage repossession actions is among Britain's highest.
The recession and technological change have cost office jobs.
Newcastle, on the other hand, suffered traumatic structural economic change
in the recession of the early 1980s, but had hoped to withstand the present
downturn. In contrast, Croydon has smaller mortgages, freeing up spending
power. It does, however, have large pockets of deprivation and long-term
unemployment.
Newcastle, with 13.8 per cent unemployment, is fighting to remain one of the
government's assisted areas - regions which qualify for financial support.
Croydon is striving to become one.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
NEWCASTLE BUSINESSES
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The centre manager
Gordon Allanson: 'People are being very much more careful. There are
still a lot of people around but they aren't buying quite as much.
They're very discerning shoppers this year.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The department store manager
Brian Forbes Turner of Bainbridge, part of the John Lewis Partnership:
'We were up by 2% last week (on the same week last year). That was an
increase for the first time in eight weeks. That's indicative it's been
tough going. Last Saturday was excellent; it had a buzz about it. I'd
think we will match last year or be slightly up.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The small businessman
James Doyle, proprietor of Watch It, clock sellers, and former general
manager of the Tick Tock chain with 32 shops which went into
receivership in January: 'I took this shop over on November 21. It's a
hell of a risk. I've now got a third mortgage on my house. We're doing
as well as we thought we would.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The shop assistant
Ann Dobbing in Gullivers, a national leather goods chain: 'It's very
busy, I don't know if it's because of our sale. You can have the shop
empty or chock-a-block; you'd think a train had tipped everybody off.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
SHOPPERS
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The family
Fireman Alan Henzell and his wife Pat live in Newcastle with their
children aged 9, 8 and 5. He earns Pounds 16,000 a year. Mrs Henzell
said: 'I think we're spending more this year, but we haven't bought it
all at once. The Sega Megadrive (computer games console) - Pounds 120
 -we've had for a few months and the portable TV's a 'buy now, pay cash
in June' offer. We'll spend over Pounds 1,000 this year. I feel worse
off.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The female shopper
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Sharon Blackburn, 21, is a personal assistant in a Northumberland
environmental consultancy, living in Tyne and Wear: 'I'm spending about
the same, Pounds 200-300. My work's great; it's a small company, there
were just four of us, now there's 10. But a lot of my family have been
made redundant; two of my uncles and a cousin have lost their jobs.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The unemployed man
Michael Cook, 32, is married with children aged 11,10 and 6. His wife
isn't earning. They live in Stanley, County Durham. 'I've been out of
work six or seven years. We'll spend Pounds 200 on the children. We
began putting money away in June. You have to give up a lot of things
as Christmas gets nearer.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The mother
Jennifer Latimer is married with a six-year-old son. Her husband is a
service engineer. They live in Chester-le-Street, County Durham.
'Nobody's bothering as much this year. My family are saying: 'Don't
bother with me,' so I haven't. I feel worse off, mainly because we
haven't had a pay rise. I've spent less, about Pounds 200.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The male shopper
Nick Booth, a doctor, is a GP in Prudhoe, Northumberland, where he
lives. He is married with three children. 'I'll spend about the same.
How much? I haven't a clue. I think things are in a mess. I see lots of
people (patients) who were hardly buying any food in November to have a
good time at Christmas.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The pensioner
Widow Jean Jackson lives in Newcastle. 'The pension doesn't go so far.
I had to go for new glasses today - Pounds 122. That's taken a big
slice out of my Christmas spending. My son could be out of work by
tomorrow; he's an accountant. The firm's going bust. We're used to
recession here.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
CROYDON BUSINESSES
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The centre manager
Rod Wood: 'Shoppers have still got their wallets padlocked. They're
taking their time and looking for the best deal. They're more
discerning and long may it reign.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The department store manager
David Batt of Allders, part of Allders Group: 'It's been slow to start.
We'll be just ahead of last year. There are some signs the recession's
abating. People seem to be spending generally less on individual gifts
but ironically there appears to be a very noticeable trend where people
are spending on better merchandise.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
