<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / ASB warns companies to abide by spirit of rulings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ACCOUNTING Standards Board has warned British companies and their
auditors that they must interpret its rulings by their spirit and not the
letter of the regulations.
In an information sheet circulated yesterday, the board's urgent issues task
force stressed that its abstracts should be guided 'by the spirit and
reasoning . . . so as to achieve their underlying purpose'.
Mr David Tweedie, ASB chairman, warned that if companies and the accountancy
profession did not follow this principle on new standards and rulings he
would be forced to introduce 'a monumental rulebook' listing every possible
permutation.
He said he was 'furious' at the way some companies had begun to interpret
board rulings by exploiting loopholes to evade their stated purpose.
'I thought we could get away from this approach,' he said.
The statement will apply to all standards, but was spurred by at least five
companies' most recent accounts which departed from the spirit of the task
force's third ruling last December.
This dealt with the treatment on disposal of goodwill - the difference
between the purchase price and the net book value of a business when it is
acquired.
Yesterday's note stressed that companies should not separate the goodwill
element from the profit or loss on disposal of an acquisition, but should
instead show it as a single item.
They should also not credit the profit-and-loss account with an amount equal
to the goodwill shown.
At least two companies have already done both of these things this year.
Mr Tweedie said that the statement was 'a pre-emptive strike'. Any other
companies that did the same might expect to be referred directly to the
Financial Reporting Review Panel, and their auditors to their own
professional bodies for possible disciplinary action.
Meanwhile, the task force is also considering proposals that would force
companies to show the costs of repurchasing their own debt in the year in
which it takes place.
The move would have a substantial effect on a significant number of
companies that are currently able to spread the effect on profits over
several years.
It comes at a time when lower interest rates have encouraged companies -
including some recently privatised utilities - to buy back higher-rate debt
and exchange it for debt at lower cost.
The task force said in a memorandum yesterday its preliminary view was that
it should require companies to recognise any profit or loss on the
repurchase immediately.
The task force has started airing its more controversial views before making
them mandatory following criticism from companies that were caught unaware
of previous changes. But a ruling could be introduced early next year.
In a separate ruling, the task force's seventh abstract stated that
companies must clearly state in their accounts the details, reasons and
effect of any departure in their accounts from the Companies Act requirement
to provide a true and fair view. This will become effective from December
23.
The Accounting Standards Board also issued a proposed amendment to SSAP 15,
the accounting standard dealing with deferred tax.
This would permit companies to make deductions net of tax annually on the
costs of any post-retirement benefits other than pensions, such as medical
costs, incurred by their employees.
Amendment to SSAP 15. Accounting for Deferred Tax. Accountancy Books, PO Box
620, Central Milton Keynes MK9 2JX. Pounds 1.50.
</TEXT>
