FT  18 DEC 92 / Case on council swaps is settled out of court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE first of a batch of nine lead cases between banks and councils over
interest-rate swap agreements has been settled out of court. This is the
latest in a steady stream of settlements since the House of Lords ruled such
contracts invalid in January last year.
The ruling left 80 banks facing losses of about Pounds 560m. They have since
sought to recover about a quarter of their losses by suing councils for
restitution of funds paid under the swap contracts.
A report in Local Government Chronicle suggests that the rest of the nine
lead cases may not now come to court following the settlement of the first
group of six lead cases last year.
The case in question, between Birmingham City Council and SG Warburg, was
due to go to court in January. The amount of the settlement has not been
disclosed.
Warburg's writ involved three swap agreements and one forward-rate
agreement, but the claim mainly concerned one swap. Warburg was trying to
recover a Pounds 5m principal payment and Pounds 5m in interest.
The leading cases, due to go to court in January, are now Westdeutsche
Landesbank Girozentrale, which is claiming Pounds 1.15m from the London
Borough of Islington, and Kleinwort Benson which is claiming Pounds 360,000
from Sandwell, West Midlands.
