<HEADLINE>
FT  18 DEC 92 / Working Party recommends guidelines for formatting of
interim accounts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ACCOUNTING Standards Board should establish guidelines for the format of
companies' interim accounts, a working party led by accountancy firm Coopers
&amp; Lybrand has recommended.
In an analysis of existing practice, the working party of accountants and
senior business executives concluded that the wide variation in existing
practices needs to be narrowed.
The details, in a report published yesterday, come when the Cadbury
committee on corporate governance is increasingly demanding greater interim
information.
The study shows that while all FTSE-100 companies include a chairman's
report in their interims, only half include balance sheet information and a
fifth show cashflow details. Just 17 per cent of these statements include
accounting policy information.
From a sample of 168 smaller companies, only a quarter provide a balance
sheet and just 2 per cent a cashflow statement. Only about 77 per cent -
against 81 per cent for FTSE-100 companies - produce any notes to the
financial statements.
The working party says the time permitted between the end of the company's
half-year and publication of the results should be cut from four months to
two.
It also argues for limited balance sheet and cashflow information, saying
that it would save costs and be quicker to produce.
Reporting by Companies on Interim Results. 0800 289520. Pounds 25.
</TEXT>
