FT  18 DEC 92 / BR deal settles slander action
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE former chairman of Permaquip, the railway track maintenance equipment
maker, has accepted Pounds 50,000 and Pounds 171,550 in legal costs from the
British Railways Board in settlement of a slander action over statements by
transport police that he had been arrested for corruption.
The High Court heard yesterday that in September 1988 British Transport
Police, investigating allegations that corrupt payments had been made to BR
personnel by contractors, raided Permaquip's offices and Mr Peter Martyn's
home in Nottinghamshire. Personal and business documents were removed.
Mr Martyn, who was at his Ravenshead home during the raid, later learnt that
one of the officers involved in the office raid had stated that he had been
arrested and was to be charged with corruption.
No accusation had been put to him by the police who raided his home and he
had no inkling that he was under suspicion.
It was later reported to Mr Martyn that on three subsequent occasions BTP
officers had made similar allegations to different people.
His slander action would have come for trial long ago but for BRB applying
repeatedly for the case to be stayed because it said police investigations
were continuing and it was likely that he would be prosecuted.
BRB finally served its defence a year ago, denying any slander had been
published and pleading qualified privilege and justification.
Last month it paid a very substantial sum of money into court to settle the
case.
Mr Martyn accepted that the payment did not amount to an admission of
liability and that the officers concerned still maintained their words were
not accurately reported to him.
</TEXT>
