FT  18 DEC 92 / Japanese curb stays
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK will continue to restrict imports of cars from Japan at least until
the end of 1994. Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade secretary, said that in the
light of the 'present economic circumstances' it would remain a restricted
market for at least a further two years.
Earlier this year the government caused consternation in the industry when
it announced it was examining the possibility of ending all restrictions on
imports of Japanese new cars from the end of this year.
A voluntary export restraint - or 'gentleman's agreement' - has existed in
the UK since 1975, limiting Japanese imports to no more than 11 per cent of
the market for new cars.
This restraint must be withdrawn from the end of this year with the start of
the single market in Europe. Last year the European Commission reached an
agreement with the Japanese government on continuing limits on direct EC
imports of cars from Japan until the end of 1999.
The agreement assumes that the UK, France, Italy, Portugal and Spain remain
restricted markets until the end of the decade, and that Japan observes
voluntary restraint on overall vehicle exports to the EC during this period.
</TEXT>
