FT  18 DEC 92 / UN troops halted by Khmer Rouge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KHMER ROUGE guerrillas in Cambodia yesterday detained 46 more United Nations
peacekeepers, only hours after releasing an earlier batch of 21, in their
latest act of defiance against the UN's Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.3bn) mission
to bring peace and democracy to the country, writes Victor Mallet in
Bangkok.
All 46 are armed Indonesian soldiers who were told by the Khmer Rouge not to
leave the village of Phum O Sala, 10km east of the central town of Kompong
Thom. They had gone there to discuss the seizure of the 21. Last night the
Indonesians were in a stand-off with about 70 armed Khmer Rouge guerrillas.
UN soldiers may fire only in self-defence, and so far none of the 16,000 UN
military personnel in Cambodia has fired a shot in anger.
