<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / International Company News: How the charges at Ford come to
more than Dollars 8bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FORD, the US carmaker, last night disclosed more than Dollars 8bn of
one-time write-offs that it said would result in the company reporting a net
loss in 1992.
The first of these is a Dollars 419m after-tax charge in the fourth quarter
of 1992, caused by the decision to reduce Ford's European workforce by about
10,000 employees during 1993.
The second charge is a Dollars 440m one-time write-off for 1992 related to
the adoption of new accounting standards governing retiree benefits, which
are in large part healthcare costs. A number of US companies are making such
one-time accountancy-related charges.
Mr Harold Poling, Ford's chairman, said these write-offs would result in a
net loss from operations for the whole of 1992.
Beyond these 1992 charges, Ford last night also announced a separate
one-time Dollars 7.5bn write-off caused by the accounting changes on
benefits and covering the period until 1992.
Ford also said it would have a Dollars 685m one-time net gain related to
accounting changes for income taxes.
In the first nine months of 1992, the Ford group made a Dollars 681.4m net
profit. The company was, however, in loss in the third quarter and has
warned that it could also be in the red in the closing three months of 1992.
The one-time charges and the gain disclosed yesterday, minus the net profits
already earned for the first nine months, point to an after-tax loss for the
whole of 1992 of nearly Dollars 7bn, a figure that could be higher if Ford
suffers an operating loss in the fourth quarter.
Ford incurred a loss of Dollars 2.26bn for the whole of 1991.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
