FT  17 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Heseltine warning on coal inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, warned yesterday that
there would be 'uncomfortable conclusions' from his department's inquiry
into the market for coal, Lisa Wood writes.
He told the employment select committee, which is investigating the proposed
closure of 31 pits, that there were still no contracts for coal when the
existing ones ran out in March, apart from a conditional contract signed by
Eastern Electricity and PowerGen this week.
British Coal and the power stations had large stocks of coal, would not need
more for a long time, and it was cheaper to import foreign coal, he told the
committee.
'That is the stark position we face. It is as stark today as in October when
I first announced it,' the secretary of state said.
