<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Move on terrorism cover broached
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Association of British Insurers yesterday made a move towards a possible
compromise in the row over insurance cover for terrorism damage, Richard
Lapper writes.
The insurance industry's trade association announced that it would consider
working with the government to cover such damage. Such a move might provide
a solution to the crisis caused when the association announced that
terrorist damage would be excluded from new commercial policies.
The association had previously insisted that the government should directly
compensate bomb and other terrorist damage, as it does in Northern Ireland.
Last week the ABI was unsympathetic to compromise solutions advanced by
industrial risk managers and insurance brokers, but yesterday Mr Tony Baker
of the ABI said the 'insurers must be as accommodating as possible'.
He said: 'A compromise must be worked out in the interests of the economy
and business.'
The shift in the ABI's position increases the pressure on the government to
support any joint initiative. Mr Baker said:'There is no way the insurance
industry can move without government support.'
The ABI said terrorism cover could be provided as a voluntary 'buy back' or
an addition to commercial policies for extra premium. That would be possible
only if insurers could limit their own exposures by obtaining reinsurance
from the government.
Letters, Page 19
</TEXT>
