<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Palestinians brace for Israeli reprisals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PALESTINIANS in the occupied territories were last night braced for tough
reprisals by the Israeli government for the kidnap and killing of a
paramilitary border police officer by Islamic fundamentalists.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, the prime minister, chaired a cabinet meeting yesterday
which discussed what ministers described as a list of options for
retaliation for the killing of Sgt-Major Nissim Toledano by guerrillas of
the Hamas Islamic movement on Tuesday. Mr Rabin said the world should expect
harsh action by Israel.
Palestinians feared that Mr Rabin, who has pledged a merciless response to
the kidnapping, would resort to mass deportations of some of the 1,200 Hamas
leaders and sympathisers rounded up in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
following Sgt-Major Toledano's kidnapping on Sunday. Such a move was called
for by a range of Israeli politicians yesterday, despite strong
international condemnation of previous deportations.
The Israeli government yesterday agreed to bail out the financially stricken
Israel Military Industries in an attempt to keep afloat one of the mainstays
of the country's big state-owned defence industry, which has been hard hit
by falling world demand for military products.
</TEXT>
